## 2. Origin Story & Founding

### Emily Steele — The Founder

Emily Steele is a Des Moines, Iowa native who graduated from Drake University in 2012 with a degree in Marketing and Public Relations. She studied at Richmond, the American International University in London. She is a self-described content creator since 2010, blogging weekly “Friday Fives” and sharing local spots on Instagram.

Prior to Hummingbirds she ran a local marketing agency called Love Local, helping local Des Moines businesses with marketing. She was also president of the Des Moines chapter of FemCity (a women’s networking group) for three years. She organised The Water Ride, an annual charity bike ride funding clean water projects in Ghana.

### Charise Flynn — The Co-Founder

Charise Flynn is an experienced tech executive who joined as COO and co-founder in 2021. She has two decades of experience scaling tech companies and raising venture capital. She previously served as COO at Dwolla (a fintech company) for over five years. She brings the operational and fundraising infrastructure that Emily lacked as a non-technical founder.

### How It Started

The concept began in 2018-2019 when Emily was running Love Local and noticed that her clients’ best marketing results came from real people sharing local experiences on Instagram. She started curating a Facebook group of Des Moines locals, bringing them together to experience and post about local businesses.

> “Hummingbirds spun out of trying an oat milk latte in Des Moines, Iowa, and sharing it on social and getting other people excited to share the small businesses in our own city.” — Emily Steele

She ran the operation entirely manually on spreadsheets — matching creators with businesses, sending briefs, tracking posts. She describes this manual phase as becoming “a very big nuisance” which prompted building the actual software platform. Charise Flynn joined in 2021 and they incorporated and launched the formal platform in 2022.

### The Name

‘Hummingbirds’ comes from a nickname Emily’s father-in-law uses for her. The metaphor fits perfectly — hummingbirds are local pollinators, always buzzing around town, spreading goodness in their communities. This became the central metaphor for the entire brand.

