## 8. The CPG Pivot — Why It Happened

### Started With Local Small Businesses

Hummingbirds launched targeting local small businesses — massage therapists, restaurants, yoga studios. The model worked but scaled poorly.

### Why Local Businesses Weren’t Enough

The sales process for local businesses is high-touch, high-effort, and low-value per client. An individual café paying $300-500 per campaign requires nearly the same sales effort as a CPG brand paying $3,000 per campaign. At national scale this unit economics problem becomes fatal.

### Why CPG Is the Perfect ICP

- **Budget:** Food/drink brands spend large amounts annually on influencer marketing. A $2,500 campaign is a rounding error.
- **Problem fit:** CPG brands are in thousands of stores nationally but can’t drive local in-store trial at city level.
- **Measurability:** CPG can track retail velocity at store level and isolate Hummingbirds markets.
- **Repeat behaviour:** OLIPOP has run 40 campaigns. Brands run 5-8 per year.
- **Expansion mechanism:** A brand’s retail distribution map becomes Hummingbirds’ expansion roadmap.

### Local Businesses Still Matter — But Differently

Local businesses (spas, restaurants, gyms) remain on the platform but serve a different purpose: they make the creator community feel authentic and local. They give creators reasons to post between CPG campaigns.

> “We don’t want to have a platform that’s only showing enterprise companies or CPG brands. They mix in well, but we’d lose the local flavour that really sets us apart.” — Emily Steele

