## 10. Creator Recruitment — How They Do It

### The Original Method — Facebook Group

Emily started Hummingbirds by bringing hundreds of Des Moines locals together in a Facebook group before building any software. The community preceded the technology.

### City-Specific Instagram Accounts

Every city Hummingbirds operates in has its own Instagram account following the naming convention [cityname]hummingbirds. Examples:

- @dsmhummingbirds — Des Moines, 5,897 followers
- @cincinnatihummingbirds — Cincinnati, 1,933 followers
- @austinhummingbirds — Austin, 1,472 followers
- @nashvillehummingbirds — Nashville, 812 followers

Bio template: ‘Everyday creators around [city]. Discover & experience brands and share about them on social media. @hummingbirdshq.’

Most accounts have exactly 9 posts — evidence of a templated launch process. Active community managers run more posts.

### New City Expansion Process

> “When we launch in a new city, we start by recruiting the first 100+ local creators to join the platform. Their authentic, community-driven campaign content then inspires the next wave of influencers to sign up — often their own friends and followers who want to get in on the fun.” — Hummingbirds blog

The Instagram search method: ‘When expanding to new cities, we look through Instagram to see who’s active, what they talk about, and how many people engage with their content.’

### The Weekly Tuesday Email

Every Tuesday, creators in active cities receive an automated email showing available campaigns in their area. This is the primary retention and activation mechanism for the creator community.

### Organic Word of Mouth

The most powerful creator recruitment mechanism is existing creators inviting friends. This is why the Referrals feature is built into the More menu.

