## 15. Strategic Lessons for nayba

### The Seven Things to Copy Exactly

1. **Manual first, platform second.** Emily ran spreadsheets until it became ‘a very big nuisance.’ Build the platform only when manual coordination is genuinely painful.
1. **B2B-first marketing.** Every piece of outward-facing content speaks to brands. Creator community is built through word of mouth, not marketing spend. Never spend marketing budget on creator acquisition.
1. **No pricing page.** Quote on call only. This protects margin, allows differentiation by brand size, and creates the sales conversation needed to understand the brand’s needs.
1. **Zero cash to creators.** In-kind perks only. This is not a budget limitation — it is the model. Cash changes the relationship from community to transaction and destroys content authenticity.
1. **Completion rate from day one.** Build accountability into the creator experience from the start. Creators who ghost campaigns should lose access to future ones.
1. **The community is first-class.** The Charm is in the main navigation, not buried in settings. Community retention is as important as campaign acquisition.
1. **City/county-specific Instagram accounts.** Launch @naybasuffolk immediately. 9 templated posts minimum. Use it to recruit creators, celebrate campaigns, and build local identity.

### The Three Things to Do Differently

1. **Counties not cities.** The UK doesn’t have the same city-identity structure as the US. Suffolk, Norfolk, Essex work better than Bury, Ipswich, Norwich.
1. **Wellness and hospitality first, CPG second.** nayba can use local wellness and hospitality campaigns as the creator recruitment vehicle while building toward the CPG model.
1. **Lucky Saint and UK challenger brands are your OLIPOP.** The UK equivalent of the CPG pivot is health/wellness/food challenger brands in Sainsbury’s and Waitrose. TRIP, Tenzing, Minor Figures, Pip & Nut.

### The Metrics That Matter — In Order

- Reels live on Instagram (the only metric that matters for the first 6 weeks)
- Creator community size (target: 100 active Suffolk creators before approaching first brand client)
- Brand campaign completion rate
- Campaign engagement rate (target: 3%+ to match Hummingbirds benchmark)
- Brand repeat rate (brands running second/third campaigns = product-market fit confirmed)
- Geographic footprint (counties active = nayba’s defensible moat)

